and":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Leslie, Fife, Scotland":"Leslie, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Leslie","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from a barony in Aberdeenshire, which is first recorded <i>c.</i> 1180 in the form <i>Lesslyn</i>, of obscure origin. Leslie in Fife is said to be named for this place; in some cases the surname may come from there.","English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Lecelin</i>, a double diminutive of <i>Lece</i>. See   Leece   and   Lesley  .","History: The Scottish Clan Leslie claims descent from Bartolf, a Hungarian nobleman who came to Scotland in 1068 or 1070 in the retinue of Queen Margaret. She was an English princess who had been born and brought up in Hungary and who went on to marry King Malcolm III of Scotland. Members of the clan have held several titles in the peerage of Scotland, including Earl of Rothes (from 1437)."],"variants":[{"name":"Leece","meanings":["English: from a medieval female personal name, <i>Lece</i>, a short form of <i>Lettice</i> (from Latin <i>Laetitia</i>, meaning ‘happiness, gaiety’).","English: variant of   Lees  .","Irish: shortened form of Gaelic <i>Mac Giolla Íosa</i>, Manx <i>Mac Guilley Yeesey</i> ‘son of <i>Giolla Íosa</i> (devotee or servant of Jesus)’. Ballaleece (‘Leece's farm’) in Kirk German was the family's main seat."]},{"name":"Lesslie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Leslie  ."]},{"name":"Lesley","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Leslie  ."]},{"name":"Laslie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Leslie  ."]},{"name":"Lessley","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Leslie  ."]},{"name":"Lasley","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Leslie  ."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When George Leslie Lord of Rothes was born about 1350, his father, Norman Leslie, was 47 and his mother, Elizabeth Kieth, was 27. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth de la Haye. He died in 1412, at the age of 63."},"et":{"Abt 1350–1412":"umbes 1350–1412","1350–1412":"1350–1412","1367–1397":"1367–1397","1380–1439":"1380–1439","1305–1365":"1305–1365","1325–1390":"1325–1390","Abt November 1365":"umbes november 1365","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1305":"1305","Abt 1350":"umbes 1350","1325":"1325","1412":"1412","1367":"1367","1365":"1365","1397":"1397","Bef February 1397":"enne veebruari 1397","Abt 1390":"umbes 1390","1439":"1439","Rhodes, Greece":"Rhodes, Notio Aigaio, Kreeka","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Leslie, Fife, Scotland":"Leslie, Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1350–1412":"noin 1350–1412","1350–1412":"1350–1412","1367–1397":"1367–1397","